# Cloud Computing Lab - Program 9

## Program 9: Deploy Java Application by Connecting to RDS Server in Cloud



Step-by-Step Execution
Step 1: Verify RDS Database

Go to:

AWS Console → RDS → Databases

Open the database:

pg05-mysql-db

Check that the status is:

Available

Copy the RDS endpoint.

Example:

pg05-mysql-db.xxxxxxxxxxxx.ap-south-1.rds.amazonaws.com

Also note:

Port: 3306
Username: admin
Password: Admin12345
Database: cloud_lab
Step 2: Verify RDS Security Group

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Security Groups → RDS-SG

The inbound rule must allow MySQL traffic:

Type: MySQL/Aurora
Protocol: TCP
Port: 3306
Source: EC2 Security Group or 0.0.0.0/0

For lab exam, if connection fails, use:

Source: 0.0.0.0/0

This allows the EC2 instance to connect to the RDS MySQL database.

Step 3: Connect to Ubuntu EC2 Instance

Open local Ubuntu terminal.

Go to the folder where the key file is present:

cd ~/Downloads

Set permission for the key file:

chmod 400 cloud-lab-key.pem

Connect to EC2:

ssh -i cloud-lab-key.pem ubuntu@EC2-PUBLIC-IP

Example:

ssh -i cloud-lab-key.pem ubuntu@13.201.xx.xx

After successful login, the terminal should show:

ubuntu@ip-10-1-1-xx:~$

Now all further commands are executed inside the EC2 Ubuntu terminal.

Step 4: Install Java JDK

Inside the EC2 terminal, first update packages:

sudo apt update -y

Install Java JDK:

sudo apt install -y default-jdk

If default-jdk does not install, use:

sudo apt install -y openjdk-21-jdk

Check Java installation:

java -version
javac -version

Expected output should show Java and Java compiler versions.

Example:

openjdk version "21..."
javac 21...
Step 5: Install MySQL Client

Install MySQL client to test RDS connection from EC2:

sudo apt install -y mysql-client

If this does not install, use:

sudo apt install -y default-mysql-client

Check MySQL client:

mysql --version
Step 6: Install MariaDB JDBC Driver

Install the JDBC driver package:

sudo apt install -y libmariadb-java

Check whether the JDBC jar file exists:

ls -l /usr/share/java/*mariadb*

Create a variable to automatically store the actual JDBC jar path:

JAR=$(ls /usr/share/java/*mariadb*.jar | head -n 1)
echo $JAR

This avoids path errors because the jar file name may differ on different Ubuntu versions.

Step 7: Test RDS Connection from EC2

Before running Java, test MySQL connection manually.

Run:

mysql -h RDS-ENDPOINT -P 3306 -u admin -p

Example:

mysql -h pg05-mysql-db.xxxxxxxxxxxx.ap-south-1.rds.amazonaws.com -P 3306 -u admin -p

Enter password:

Admin12345

After successful connection, MySQL prompt appears:

mysql>

Run:

SHOW DATABASES;

Use the database:

USE cloud_lab;

Check tables:

SHOW TABLES;

Exit MySQL:

EXIT;

This confirms that EC2 can connect to the RDS database.

Step 8: Create Java Program

Inside the EC2 terminal, create the Java file:

nano JdbcCrudDemo.java

Paste the following code.

Replace RDS-ENDPOINT with your actual RDS endpoint.

import java.sql.*;

public class JdbcCrudDemo {

    static final String JDBC_URL = "jdbc:mariadb://RDS-ENDPOINT:3306/cloud_lab";
    static final String JDBC_USER = "admin";
    static final String JDBC_PASS = "Admin12345";

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        try {
            Class.forName("org.mariadb.jdbc.Driver");

            Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(JDBC_URL, JDBC_USER, JDBC_PASS);
            System.out.println("Connected to RDS successfully.");

            Statement createStmt = conn.createStatement();

            createStmt.executeUpdate(
                "CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS employees (" +
                "id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY, " +
                "name VARCHAR(50), " +
                "email VARCHAR(100), " +
                "country VARCHAR(50), " +
                "salary DOUBLE)"
            );

            createStmt.executeUpdate("DELETE FROM employees");

            String insertSql = "INSERT INTO employees (name, email, country, salary) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?)";
            PreparedStatement insertStmt = conn.prepareStatement(insertSql);

            insertStmt.setString(1, "Alice");
            insertStmt.setString(2, "alice@example.com");
            insertStmt.setString(3, "USA");
            insertStmt.setDouble(4, 50000);
            insertStmt.executeUpdate();

            System.out.println("Inserted new employee.");

            String selectSql = "SELECT * FROM employees";
            Statement selectStmt = conn.createStatement();
            ResultSet rs = selectStmt.executeQuery(selectSql);

            System.out.println("Employee List:");
            while (rs.next()) {
                System.out.println(
                    rs.getInt("id") + ", " +
                    rs.getString("name") + ", " +
                    rs.getString("email") + ", " +
                    rs.getString("country") + ", " +
                    rs.getDouble("salary")
                );
            }

            String updateSql = "UPDATE employees SET salary = ? WHERE name = ?";
            PreparedStatement updateStmt = conn.prepareStatement(updateSql);

            updateStmt.setDouble(1, 60000);
            updateStmt.setString(2, "Alice");
            updateStmt.executeUpdate();

            System.out.println("Updated salary for Alice.");

            String deleteSql = "DELETE FROM employees WHERE name = ?";
            PreparedStatement deleteStmt = conn.prepareStatement(deleteSql);

            deleteStmt.setString(1, "Alice");
            deleteStmt.executeUpdate();

            System.out.println("Deleted employee Alice.");

            rs.close();
            selectStmt.close();
            insertStmt.close();
            updateStmt.close();
            deleteStmt.close();
            createStmt.close();
            conn.close();

            System.out.println("Program executed successfully.");

        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

Save the file:

Ctrl + O
Enter
Ctrl + X
Step 9: Compile Java Program

Use the JDBC jar variable created earlier:

JAR=$(ls /usr/share/java/*mariadb*.jar | head -n 1)
echo $JAR

Compile the program:

javac -cp "$JAR" JdbcCrudDemo.java

If there is no error, compilation is successful.

Check files:

ls

Expected files:

JdbcCrudDemo.java
JdbcCrudDemo.class
Step 10: Run Java Program

Run the program:

java -cp ".:$JAR" JdbcCrudDemo

Expected output:

Connected to RDS successfully.
Inserted new employee.
Employee List:
1, Alice, alice@example.com, USA, 50000.0
Updated salary for Alice.
Deleted employee Alice.
Program executed successfully.

